İzmir Atatürk Stadium.label: İzmir Atatürk Stadium
İzmir Atatürk Stadium.description: İzmir Atatürk Stadium is a multi-purpose stadium in İzmir, Turkey. It is currently used mostly for football matches. The stadium holds 51,295 people. It was built in 1964, and most recently refurbished in 2005. Wikipedia

İzmir Halkapınar Sport Hall.label: İzmir Halkapınar Sport Hall
İzmir Halkapınar Sport Hall.description: İzmir Halkapınar Sport Hall is an indoor multi-purpose sport venue that is located in the Halkapınar neighborhood of İzmir, Turkey. The hall has a seating capacity of 10,000 spectators. Wikipedia

AT&T Park.label: AT&T Park
AT&T Park.description: AT&T Park is a ballpark primarily used for hosting Major League Baseball games. It is located in the South of Market neighborhood of San Francisco, California, at 24 Willie Mays Plaza, at the corner of Third and King Streets. Wikipedia

Auestadion.label: Auestadion
Auestadion.description: Auestadion is a multi-use stadium in Kassel, Germany close to the Karlsaue park. It is used mostly for football matches and is the home stadium of KSV Hessen Kassel. The stadium is able to hold 18000 people. Wikipedia

BMO Field.label: BMO Field
BMO Field.description: BMO Field is a Canadian soccer stadium located in Exhibition Place in the city of Toronto. The open-air structure can seat up to 21,566 spectators in it's standard configuation for soccer. Wikipedia

Baku Tennis Academy.label: Baku Tennis Academy
Baku Tennis Academy.description: Baku Tennis Academy, is a tennis venue in Baku, Azerbaijan. The center currently hosts the Baku Cup. The main stadium has a capacity of 10,000 people. The central court has a capacity of 3,000, and the other 12 courts have a capacity of 200. Wikipedia

Boleyn Ground.label: Boleyn Ground
Boleyn Ground.description: The Boleyn Ground, often referred to as Upton Park due to its location in Upton Park, London, is the football stadium of West Ham United F.C. playing in the Premier League. The stadium has a capacity of 35,016. Wikipedia

Buffalo Memorial Auditorium.label: Buffalo Memorial Auditorium
Buffalo Memorial Auditorium.description: Buffalo Memorial Auditorium was an indoor arena in downtown Buffalo, New York. It hosted the Buffalo Bisons of the AHL, the Buffalo Sabres of the NHL, the Buffalo Braves of the NBA, the Buffalo Stallions ... Wikipedia

Cardiff City Stadium.label: Cardiff City Stadium
Cardiff City Stadium.description: The Cardiff City Stadium is a Premier League football stadium in the Leckwith area of Cardiff, Wales. It is the home of Cardiff City Football Club. The stadium replaced Ninian Park as Cardiff City's home ground in 2009. Wikipedia

Carrow Road.label: Carrow Road
Carrow Road.description: Carrow Road is a football stadium located in Norwich, England, and is the home of Premier League club Norwich City F.C.. The stadium is located toward the easterly end of the city, not far from Norwich railway station and the River Wensum. Wikipedia

City Ground.label: City Ground
City Ground.description: The City Ground is a football stadium in the West Bridgford area of Nottingham, Nottinghamshire, England, on the banks of the River Trent. It has been home to Nottingham Forest Football Club since 1898, and has an all-seated capacity of 30,602. Wikipedia

Commonwealth Stadium (Edmonton).label: Commonwealth Stadium
Commonwealth Stadium (Edmonton).description: Commonwealth Stadium is an open-air, all-seater multipurpose stadium located in the McCauley neighbourhood of the Canadian city of Edmonton, Alberta. Wikipedia

Craven Cottage.label: Craven Cottage
Craven Cottage.description: Craven Cottage is the name of a football stadium located in Fulham, London. It has been the home ground of the Premier League club Fulham F.C. since 1896. Wikipedia

DKB-Arena.label: DKB-Arena
DKB-Arena.description: The DKB-Arena, previously known as Ostseestadion, is the home stadium of F.C. Hansa Rostock, a German football club, located in the city of Rostock. Wikipedia

DW Stadium.label: DW Stadium
DW Stadium.description: The DW Stadium is a sports stadium in Wigan, Greater Manchester, England, that is leased by Wigan Athletic football club, and home to Wigan Warriors Rugby League, the most successful team in World Rugby League. Wikipedia

Dnipro Arena.label: Dnipro-Arena
Dnipro Arena.description: Dnipro-Arena is a football stadium in Dnipropetrovsk, Ukraine. It is mostly for football matches and hosts the homes matches of FC Dnipro Dnipropetrovsk. The stadium has a capacity of 31,003 people. It replaced Dnipro's old Soviet Metalurh Stadium. Wikipedia

Donbass Arena.label: Donbass Arena
Donbass Arena.description: Donbass Arena or Donbas Arena is a stadium with a natural grass pitch in Donetsk, Ukraine that opened on 29 August 2009. The facility is located in the center of the city, in the Lenin Comsomol park. Wikipedia

Espenmoos.label: Espenmoos
Espenmoos.description: Espenmoos Stadium, is a football stadium in St. Gallen, Switzerland. It was the home ground of the FC St. Gallen until their current stadium AFG Arena opened in 2008. The stadium has since been demolished except for the main seated stand. Wikipedia

Estadio Miguel Grau (Piura).label: Estadio Miguel Grau
Estadio Miguel Grau (Piura).description: Estadio Miguel Grau is a multi-use stadium in Piura, Peru, built in 1958. It is currently used by football team Atlético Grau. Throughout the years the stadium has undergone many renovations, most recently for the Copa America 2004. Wikipedia

Ewood Park.label: Ewood Park
Ewood Park.description: Ewood Park is a football stadium in the English town of Blackburn, Lancashire, and is the home of Blackburn Rovers Football Club — one of the founder members of the Football League and Premier League. Wikipedia

FC Dallas Stadium.label: FC Dallas Stadium
FC Dallas Stadium.description: Toyota Stadium is a soccer-specific stadium with a 20,500-seat capacity, built and owned by the city of Frisco, Texas. Wikipedia

FK Viktoria Stadion.label: FK Viktoria Stadion
FK Viktoria Stadion.description: FK Viktoria Stadion, officially known as eFotbal Arena for sponsorship reasons, is a multi-use stadium in Prague, Czech Republic. It is currently used mostly for football matches and is the home ground of FK Viktoria Žižkov. Wikipedia

Florence Civic Center.label: Florence Civic Center
Florence Civic Center.description: The Florence Civic Center is a 10,000-seat multipurpose arena in Florence, South Carolina. It hosted the infamous eighth WWF In Your House pay-per-view in 1996, during which a storm knocked out the ... Wikipedia

Ford Field.label: Ford Field
Ford Field.description: Ford Field is an indoor American football stadium located in Downtown Detroit. It is the home field of the National Football League's Detroit Lions. It is owned by the Detroit/Wayne County Stadium Authority. Wikipedia

Fraport Arena.label: Fraport Arena
Fraport Arena.description: Fraport Arena is an arena in Frankfurt, Germany. It is primarily used for basketball and is the home arena of Fraport Skyliners. The arena opened in 1986 and holds 5,000 people. Wikipedia

GelreDome.label: GelreDome
GelreDome.description: The GelreDome is a football stadium in the city of Arnhem, in the Netherlands. It serves as the home of the football club Vitesse. Wikipedia

Glücksgas Stadium.label: Glücksgas Stadium
Glücksgas Stadium.description: Glücksgas Stadium is a football stadium in Dresden, Saxony. It is the current home of Dynamo Dresden. The facility is known as the Rudolf-Harbig-Stadion or Dynamo Stadion. Wikipedia

Goodison Park.label: Goodison Park
Goodison Park.description: Goodison Park is a football stadium located in Walton, Liverpool, England. The stadium has been home to Premier League club Everton F.C. since its completion in 1892 and is one of the world's oldest purpose-built football grounds. Wikipedia

Halifax Metro Centre.label: Halifax Metro Centre
Halifax Metro Centre.description: The Halifax Metro Centre is a multi-purpose indoor sporting arena located in downtown Halifax, Nova Scotia, Canada. The building is next to the World Trade and Convention Centre, at the foot of Citadel Hill. It is the largest arena in Halifax. Wikipedia

Hallenstadion.label: Hallenstadion
Hallenstadion.description:
The Hallenstadion is a multi-purpose facility and is mainly home to the ZSC Lions of the National League A, in the Swiss city of Zürich.
Designed by Bruno Giacometti, it opened on July 18, 1939, and was renovated in 2005. Wikipedia

Hypo-Arena.label: Hypo-Arena
Hypo-Arena.description: Wörthersee Stadion is a multi-purpose stadium in Klagenfurt, Austria. It is the home ground of Austria Klagenfurt, currently playing in the Austrian Regional League Central. Wikipedia

Kajot Arena.label: Kajot Arena
Kajot Arena.description: Kajot Arena, formerly known as Starobrno Rondo Aréna and Hala Rondo, is an indoor arena in Brno, Czech Republic. The capacity of the arena is 7,200 people and it was built in 1982. It is currently home to the HC Kometa Brno ice hockey team. Wikipedia

Kinnarps Arena.label: Kinnarps Arena
Kinnarps Arena.description:
Kinnarps Arena is an ice hockey venue in Jönköping, Sweden.
The arena, which is located in the Rosenlund district of Jönköping, was built between September 1999 and September 2000. Wikipedia

Lerkendal Stadion.label: Lerkendal Stadion
Lerkendal Stadion.description: Lerkendal Stadion is an all-seater football stadium located at Lerkendal in Trondheim, Norway. The home ground of the Tippeligaen side Rosenborg BK, it has a capacity for 21,166 spectators, making it ... Wikipedia

Letzigrund.label: Letzigrund
Letzigrund.description: Letzigrund is a stadium in Zurich, Switzerland, and the home of the football club FC Zürich. It is also temporarily home to the football club Grasshopper Club Zürich while their stadium is under construction. Wikipedia

Livestrong Sporting Park.label: Sporting Park
Livestrong Sporting Park.description: Sporting Park is a soccer-specific stadium in Kansas City, Kansas, US, and is the home of Sporting Kansas City. The stadium was renamed in January 2013 after the Livestrong Foundation and Sporting Kansas City ended their agreement. Wikipedia

Lohrheidestadion.label: Lohrheidestadion
Lohrheidestadion.description: The Lohrheidestadion is a multi-use stadium in Bochum-Wattenscheid, Germany. It is currently used mostly for football matches and is the home stadium of SG Wattenscheid 09. The stadium is able to hold 16,233 people and opened in 1954. Wikipedia

Marschweg-Stadion.label: Marschweg-Stadion
Marschweg-Stadion.description: Marschweg-Stadion is a multi-use stadium in Oldenburg, Germany . It is used as the stadium of VfB Oldenburg matches. The capacity of the stadium is 15,000 spectators. Wikipedia

Max-Schmeling-Halle.label: Max-Schmeling-Halle
Max-Schmeling-Halle.description: Max-Schmeling-Halle is a multi-purpose arena, in Berlin, Germany, named after the famous German boxer Max Schmeling. Apart from the Velodrom, it's one of Berlin's biggest indoor sports arenas and holds from 8,861 people, up to 11,000 people. Wikipedia

Melbourne Multi Purpose Venue.label: Melbourne Multi Purpose Venue
Melbourne Multi Purpose Venue.description: Hisense Arena is a sports venue that is part of the Melbourne Park complex, in Melbourne, Victoria, Australia. The arena's current name was purchased in July 2008. Wikipedia

Na Litavce.label: Na Litavce
Na Litavce.description: Na Litavce is a football stadium in Příbram, Czech Republic. It is currently used as the home ground of 1. FK Příbram. The stadium holds 9,100 people. Wikipedia

Na Stínadlech.label: Na Stínadlech
Na Stínadlech.description: Na Stinadlech is a multi-purpose stadium in Teplice, Czech Republic. It is currently used mostly for football matches and is the home ground of FK Teplice. The stadium holds 18,221 and was built in 1973. Wikipedia

National Stadium, Warsaw.label: National Stadium, Warsaw
National Stadium, Warsaw.description: The National Stadium is a retractable roof football stadium located in Warsaw, Poland. It is used mostly for football matches and it is the home stadium of Poland national football team. Wikipedia

O2 World (Hamburg).label: O2 World
O2 World (Hamburg).description: O2 World Hamburg is a multi-purpose arena in Hamburg, Germany. It opened in 2002 and can hold up to 16,000 people. It is located adjacent to the football stadium Imtech Arena and the new Volksbank Arena in the Bahrenfeld district. Wikipedia

EWE Arena.label: Small EWE Arena
EWE Arena.description: EWE Arena is a dual indoor sporting arena complex that is located in Oldenburg, Germany. It is a part of the Weser-Ems Halle multi-sporting complex. It contains two main arena halls, the Small EWE Arena, and the Large EWE Arena. Wikipedia

Ombaka National Stadium.label: Ombaka National Stadium
Ombaka National Stadium.description: Ombaka National Stadium is a multi-use stadium in Benguela, Angola. Completed in 2010, it is used mostly for football matches and has hosted some events for the 2010 African Cup of Nations. The stadium has a capacity of 35,000 people. Wikipedia

Pabellón Multiusos Fontes do Sar.label: Pabellón Multiusos Fontes do Sar
Pabellón Multiusos Fontes do Sar.description:
Pavillón Multiusos Fontes do Sar is a multi-purpose sports arena in Santiago de Compostela, Galicia, Spain.
It is owned and operated by Santiago de Compostela city council. Wikipedia

Palacio de Deportes de la Comunidad de M.label: Palacio de Deportes de la Comunidad de Madrid
Palacio de Deportes de la Comunidad de M.description: Palacio de Deportes de la Comunidad de Madrid is an indoor sporting arena located in the City of Madrid, Spain. Its capacity is 15,000 people for basketball matches, 14,000 for handball matches and 18,000 for concerts. Wikipedia

Palais Omnisports de Paris-Bercy.label: Palais Omnisports de Paris-Bercy
Palais Omnisports de Paris-Bercy.description: Opened in 1984, Palais Omnisports de Paris-Bercy, often abbreviated as POPB or Bercy, is an indoor sports arena and concert hall on boulevard de Bercy located in the 12th arrondissement of Paris. The closest métro station is Bercy. Wikipedia

Pankritio Stadium.label: Pankritio Stadium
Pankritio Stadium.description: Pankritio Stadium is a sports stadium located in Heraklion on the island of Crete. It was completed on December 31, 2003, and officially opened on August 11, 2004, just before the beginning of the 2004 ... Wikipedia

Paul-Janes-Stadion.label: Paul-Janes-Stadion
Paul-Janes-Stadion.description: The Paul-Janes-Stadion in Düsseldorf-Flingern is one of the home grounds of Fortuna Düsseldorf. It was built in 1930 by the team; now city-owned, it has been named since 1990 after the long-standing ... Wikipedia

Porsche-Arena.label: Porsche-Arena
Porsche-Arena.description: Porsche Arena is a multi-purpose arena, located in Stuttgart, Germany. The seating capacity of the arena varies, from 5,100 to 8,000 people and it was opened in 2006, after 14 months of construction. Wikipedia

Råsunda Stadium.label: Råsunda Stadium
Råsunda Stadium.description: Råsunda Fotbollstadion, also known as Råsundastadion, Råsunda Stadium or just Råsunda, was the former Swedish national football stadium. It is located in Solna Municipality in Stockholm and named after the district in Solna where it is located. Wikipedia

Raymond James Stadium.label: Raymond James Stadium
Raymond James Stadium.description: Raymond James Stadium, also known as the "Ray Jay", is a multi-purpose football stadium located in Tampa, Florida. It is home to the NFL's Tampa Bay Buccaneers as well as the NCAA's South Florida Bulls football team. Wikipedia

Rheinlandhalle.label: Rheinlandhalle
Rheinlandhalle.description: Rheinlandhalle, is an arena in Krefeld, Germany. It is primarily used for ice hockey, and was home to the Krefeld Pinguine of the Deutsche Eishockey Liga until the König Palast opened in 2004. It opened in 1955 and holds 6,714 spectators. Wikipedia

Rheinstadion.label: Rheinstadion
Rheinstadion.description:
The Rheinstadion was a multi-purpose stadium, in Düsseldorf, Germany. The stadium was built, near the Rhine, in 1926 and held 55,900 people, at the end of its life.
It was the home ground for Fortuna Düsseldorf from 1953–1970 and 1972–2002. Wikipedia

Robertson Stadium.label: Robertson Stadium
Robertson Stadium.description: John O'Quinn Field at Corbin J. Robertson Stadium was a multi-purpose stadium in Houston, located on the campus of the University of Houston. It was the home of the Houston Cougars football and women's soccer teams. Wikipedia

Roker Park.label: Roker Park
Roker Park.description: Roker Park was an English football stadium situated in Roker, Sunderland. The stadium was the home of the English football club Sunderland A.F.C. from 1897 to 1997 before the club moved to the Stadium of Light. Wikipedia

Roos Field.label: Roos Field
Roos Field.description: Roos Field is an outdoor college football stadium on the campus of Eastern Washington University in Cheney, Washington, U.S. It is home to the Eastern Washington Eagles of the Big Sky Conference in Division I. Wikipedia

Südweststadion.label: Südweststadion
Südweststadion.description: Südweststadion is a multi-purpose stadium in Ludwigshafen am Rhein, Germany. The stadium holds 6,100 people and was built in 1950. It is currently used mostly for football matches and is the home of FSV Oggersheim. Wikipedia

SAP Arena.label: SAP Arena
SAP Arena.description: SAP Arena is a multi-purpose arena in Mannheim, Germany. It is primarily used for ice hockey and handball, and is the home arena of the Adler Mannheim ice hockey club and the "Rhein-Neckar-Löwen" handball club. Wikipedia

SGL arena.label: SGL arena
SGL arena.description: SGL arena, until 1 July 2011 the Impuls Arena, is a football stadium in Augsburg, Bavaria, Germany. It is used mostly for football matches and hosts the home matches of FC Augsburg. Wikipedia

SNP Stadium.label: SNP Stadium
SNP Stadium.description: The SNP Stadium is a multi-purpose stadium in Banská Bystrica, Slovakia. It is currently used mostly for football matches and is the home ground of FK Dukla Banská Bystrica. The stadium has a capacity of 10,000, with 7,380 seats. Wikipedia

Siemens Arena.label: Siemens Arena
Siemens Arena.description: Siemens Arena, located in Šeškinė elderate of Vilnius, is the second largest arena in Lithuania. It generally hosts basketball games as well as concerts. The arena opened on October 30, 2004. Wikipedia

Sparkassen-Arena.label: Sparkassen-Arena
Sparkassen-Arena.description:
The Sparkassen-Arena is an indoor arena, in Kiel, Germany.
It is primarily used by THW Kiel and as a venue for rock/pop concerts. It holds up to 13,500 people. Wikipedia

Sporthalle (Cologne).label: Sporthalle
Sporthalle (Cologne).description: Sporthalle was an indoor arena in Cologne, Germany. It was primarily used for basketball and other indoor sporting events until it closed due to the larger Lanxess Arena opening. The arena held 8,000 spectators and opened in 1958. Wikipedia

St Andrew's (stadium).label: St Andrew's
St Andrew's (stadium).description: St Andrew's is an association football stadium in the Bordesley district of Birmingham, England. It has been the home ground of Birmingham City Football Club for more than a century. Wikipedia

Stade Maurice Boyau.label: Stade Maurice Boyau
Stade Maurice Boyau.description: Stade Maurice Boyau is a multi-use stadium in Dax, France. It is currently used mostly for rugby union matches and is the home stadium of US Dax. The stadium is able to hold 15,000 people. Wikipedia

Stade Olympique de Sousse.label: Stade Olympique de Sousse
Stade Olympique de Sousse.description: Stade Olympique de Sousse is a multi-purpose stadium in Sousse, Tunisia. It is used by the football team Etoile Sahel, and was used for the 2004 African Cup of Nations. The stadium holds 30,000 people. Wikipedia

Stade d'Angondjé.label: Stade d'Angondjé
Stade d'Angondjé.description: The Stade d'Angondjé is a stadium in Angondjé, a suburb of Libreville in Gabon. It is referred to as Stade de l'Amitié. The stadium build was expected to take 20 months and was funded by the Gabonese and Chinese governments. Wikipedia

Stade de Franceville.label: Stade de Franceville
Stade de Franceville.description: The Stade de Franceville is a stadium in Franceville, Gabon. The 35000 capacity stadium was opened in January 2012, in time for its use in the 2012 African Cup of Nations. The opening game was a friendly between Gabon and Sudan. Wikipedia

Stade de la Libération.label: Stade de la Libération
Stade de la Libération.description: Stade de la Libération is a multi-use stadium in Boulogne-sur-Mer, France. It is currently used mostly for football matches and is the home stadium of US Boulogne. The stadium is able to hold 15,034 people. Wikipedia

Stade de la Route de Lorient.label: Stade de la Route de Lorient
Stade de la Route de Lorient.description: The Stade de la Route de Lorient is a football stadium, inaugurated on September 15, 1912. It is located at 111 route de Lorient, in west-central Rennes. Rebuilt in 2001 and able to seat 29,376, the stadium is currently the home of Stade Rennais. Wikipedia

Stadion Miejski (Wrocław).label: Stadion Miejski
Stadion Miejski (Wrocław).description: The Municipal Stadium in Wrocław, Poland, is the highest fourth category football stadium built for the 2012 UEFA European Football Championship. The Stadium is located on aleja Śląska in the western part of the city. Wikipedia

Stadion am Zoo.label: Stadion am Zoo
Stadion am Zoo.description: The Stadion am Zoo is a multi-purpose stadium in Wuppertal, Germany. It is currently used mostly for football matches and hosts the home matches of Wuppertaler SV. The stadium is able to hold 23,067 people and was built in 1924. Wikipedia

Stadion an der Kreuzeiche.label: Stadion an der Kreuzeiche
Stadion an der Kreuzeiche.description: Stadion an der Kreuzeiche is a multi-use stadium in Reutlingen, Germany. It is used mostly for football matches and is the home stadium of SSV Reutlingen. The stadium is able to hold 15,228 people and was opened in 1953. Wikipedia

Stadion der Freundschaft (Cottbus).label: Stadion der Freundschaft
Stadion der Freundschaft (Cottbus).description: The Stadion der Freundschaft is a football stadium in Cottbus, Germany. The home ground of FC Energie Cottbus, originally opened in 1930, has a capacity of 22,528. Wikipedia

Stadion města Plzně.label: Doosan Arena
Stadion města Plzně.description: Doosan Arena, previously known as Stadion města Plzně is a multi-purpose stadium in Plzeň, Czech Republic. It is located in the Štrunc Park near the confluence of Mže and Radbuza rivers. Wikipedia

Stadion u Nisy.label: Stadion u Nisy
Stadion u Nisy.description: Stadion u Nisy is an all-seater football stadium in Liberec. The stadium is home to Czech football club FC Slovan Liberec and occasionally hosts matches of the Czech Republic national team. Wikipedia

Stadionul Dan Păltinişanu.label: Stadionul Dan Păltinișanu
Stadionul Dan Păltinişanu.description: Stadionul Dan Paltinisanu is a multi-purpose stadium in Timişoara, Romania. It is currently used mostly for football matches by the local team, Poli Timişoara. Wikipedia

Stožice Sports Park.label: Stožice Sports Park
Stožice Sports Park.description: Stožice Sports Park is a new multi-use sports complex in Ljubljana, Slovenia, that hosts all departments of Olimpija Ljubljana sports club, former women's European club champions Krim and other Ljubljana ... Wikipedia

Sun Life Stadium.label: Sun Life Stadium
Sun Life Stadium.description: Sun Life Stadium is an American football stadium in Miami Gardens, Florida, a suburb of Miami. It is the home stadium of the Miami Dolphins National Football League team, and the University of Miami Hurricanes football team. Wikipedia

TUI Arena.label: TUI Arena
TUI Arena.description: TUI Arena is an arena in Hanover, Germany. The arena opened in 2000 and holds 10,767, during hockey or handball matches and up to 14,000, during concerts. Wikipedia

Tehelné pole.label: Tehelné pole
Tehelné pole.description: Tehelné pole is a neighborhood in Bratislava, Slovakia, characterized by the presence of several sports facilities. Administratively, the neighborhood belongs to Nové Mesto borough, situated around 5 km north-east of the centre. Wikipedia

The Hawthorns.label: The Hawthorns
The Hawthorns.description: The Hawthorns is an all-seater football stadium in West Bromwich, Sandwell, England, with a capacity of 26,445. It did hold 28,100 up until The Halfords Lane stand lost seats through refurbishment. Wikipedia

Tivoli-Neu.label: Tivoli-Neu
Tivoli-Neu.description: Tivoli-Neu is a multi-purpose stadium in Innsbruck, Austria. It is currently used mostly for football matches and is the home ground of FC Wacker Innsbruck and Swarco Raiders Tirol. The stadium capacity was 17,400 when it was built in 2000. Wikipedia

Toyota Park (Bridgeview).label: Toyota Park
Toyota Park (Bridgeview).description: Toyota Park is a soccer-specific stadium located at 71st Street and Harlem Avenue in Bridgeview, Illinois, about 12 miles southwest from downtown Chicago. It is the home stadium of the Chicago Fire Soccer Club, members of Major League Soccer. Wikipedia

Trolli Arena.label: Trolli Arena
Trolli Arena.description: The Trolli Arena is a football stadium in the district of Ronhof in Fürth, Bavaria, and the home ground of 2. Bundesliga team SpVgg Greuther Fürth. Wikipedia

Vaillant Arena.label: Vaillant Arena
Vaillant Arena.description: Vaillant Arena is an arena in Davos, Switzerland. It is primarily used for ice hockey and is the home arena of HC Davos. It holds 7,080 people, of which 3,280 are seated. Every year the Spengler Cup is played in this arena. Wikipedia

Victoria Stadium (Gibraltar).label: Victoria Stadium
Victoria Stadium (Gibraltar).description: Victoria Stadium is a multi-purpose stadium in Gibraltar. It is currently used mostly for football matches and holds about 5,000 people. It is located close to the Gibraltar Airport just off Winston Churchill Avenue. Wikipedia

Villa Park.label: Villa Park
Villa Park.description: Villa Park is a football stadium in the district of Witton, Birmingham, England, with a seating capacity of 42,682. It has been the home of Aston Villa Football Club since 1897. Wikipedia

Volkswagen Arena.label: Volkswagen Arena
Volkswagen Arena.description: Volkswagen Arena is a multi-purpose stadium in Wolfsburg, Lower Saxony, Germany and serves as the home stadium of the 2008–09 Bundesliga champions VfL Wolfsburg. The Volkswagen Arena replaced the former stadium of VfL Wolfsburg, the VFL Stadion. Wikipedia

Werk Arena.label: Werk Arena
Werk Arena.description:
Werk Arena is an indoor sporting arena located in Třinec, Czech Republic. The capacity of the arena is 5,200 people of which 3700 are seats.
The arena was built in 1967, the roof was provided in 1976. Wikipedia

White City Stadium.label: White City Stadium
White City Stadium.description: White City Stadium was built in White City, London, for the 1908 Summer Olympics and is often seen as the precursor to the modern seater stadium and noted for hosting the finish of the first modern distance marathon. Wikipedia

Wiener Stadthalle.label: Wiener Stadthalle
Wiener Stadthalle.description: Wiener Stadthalle is an indoor arena, located in the 15th district of Vienna, Austria. It was designed by Austrian architect Roland Rainer and built from 1953–1958. The arena has an overall seating capacity of approximately 16,000 people. Wikipedia

Wormatia-Stadion.label: Wormatia-Stadion
Wormatia-Stadion.description: EWR-Arena is a multi-use stadium in Worms, Germany. It is currently used mostly for football matches and is the home of Wormatia Worms. The stadium has a capacity of 5,724 people. Wikipedia

Zimní stadion Hradec Králové.label: Zimní stadion Hradec Králové
Zimní stadion Hradec Králové.description: Zimní stadion Hradec Králové, is an arena in Hradec Králové, Czech Republic. It is primarily used for ice hockey, and is the home to the HC VCES Hradec Králové of the Czech Extraliga. It opened in 1957 and holds 7,700 spectators. Wikipedia

Ōita Bank Dome.label: Ōita Bank Dome
Ōita Bank Dome.description:
Ōita Bank Dome is a multi-purpose stadium in the city of Ōita in Ōita Prefecture on Kyushu Island in Japan.
The stadium is currently called Ōita Bank Dome, or Daigin Dome as an abbreviated form, by naming rights. Wikipedia

Şükrü Saracoğlu Stadium.label: Şükrü Saracoğlu Stadium
Şükrü Saracoğlu Stadium.description: Şükrü Saracoğlu Stadium, is a football stadium in the Kadıköy district of Istanbul, Turkey, and is the home venue of Fenerbahçe S.K. It was inaugurated in 1908 and renovated between 1999 and 2006. Wikipedia
